{"title_page": "Leon Russell", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Leon Russell\n| image         = Leon Russell Billboard.jpg\n| caption       = Russell c. 1970\n| birth_name    = Claude Russell Bridges\n| alias         = Leon Russell, Hank Wilson, Russell Bridges\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|mf=y|1942|04|02}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lawton, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|mf=y|2016|11|13|1942|04|02}}\n| death_place   = [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| spouse        = {{Plainlist|\n* {{Marriage|Mary McCreary|20 June 1975|3 October 1980}}{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* {{Marriage|Jan Bridges (Janet Lee Constantine)|6 February 1983|13 November 2016}}{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n| children      = 6\n| occupation    = Musician, singer-songwriter\n| years_active  = 1956\u20132016\n\n| module        = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| label  = {{hlist|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]|[[Shelter Records|Shelter]]|[[Paradise Records|Paradise]]|Leon Russell Records|[[Virgin Records]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[J. J. Cale]]|[[Marc Benno]]|[[New Grass Revival]]|[[George Harrison]]|[[Bob Dylan]]|[[Eric Clapton]]|[[Willie Nelson]]|[[Neil Young]]|[[Elton John]]|[[Rita Coolidge]]|[[Joe Cocker]]|[[Edgar Winter]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Keyboards|vocals|bass guitar|guitar|baritone horn|harpsichord}}\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Country music|country]]|[[Rock music|rock]]|[[Folk music|folk]]|[[gospel music|gospel]]|[[bluegrass music|bluegrass]]|[[rhythm and blues|R&B]]|[[folk rock]]|[[blues rock]]|[[surf music|surf]]|[[swamp rock]]|[[Tulsa Sound]]}}\n| background       = solo_singer\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Leon Russell''' (born '''Claude Russell Bridges'''; April 2, 1942<ref name=\"NYT-2016\"/> \u2013 November 13, 2016) was an American musician and songwriter who was involved with numerous bestselling [[pop music]] records during his 60-year career. His genres included [[Pop music|pop]], [[Country music|country]], [[Rock music|rock]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[gospel music|gospel]], [[bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[rhythm and blues]], [[folk rock]], [[blues rock]], [[surf music|surf]], [[traditional pop music|standards]], and [[Tulsa Sound]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thechurchstudio.com/leon-russell/|title=Leon Russell|website=Thechurchstudio.com|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis collaborations rank as some of the most successful in music history, and as a touring musician he performed with hundreds of notable artists.<ref>{{cite web | author=Jason Ankeny | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/leon-russell-mn0000816387/biography | title=Leon Russell &#124; Biography & History | website=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> He recorded 33 albums<ref name=\"Softshoe\"/> and at least 430 songs.<ref>[https://www.earnthenecklace.com/top-7-songs-of-leon-russell-to-remember-the-talented-singer/ \"Top 7 Songs of Leon Russell to Remember the Talented Singer\"]. Earnthenecklace.com.</ref> He wrote \"[[Joe Cocker!|Delta Lady]]\", recorded by [[Joe Cocker]], and organized and performed with Cocker's [[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (album)|''Mad Dogs and Englishmen'']] tour in 1970.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://assets.nydailynews.com/polopoly_fs/1.2053755.1419279605!/img/httpImage/image.jpg_gen/derivatives/gallery_1200/joe-cocker-leon-russell-1970.jpg | title=Joe Cocker and Russell performing during the \"Mad Dogs and Englishmen\" tour | website=Assets.nydailynews.com | accessdate=January 25, 2018}}</ref> His \"[[A Song for You]]\", added to the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]] in 2018,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/david-bowie-whitney-houston-dr-dre-recordings-added-grammy-hall-fame | title=Meet The Grammy Hall Of Fame Class Of 2018 | publisher=[[The Recording Academy]] | date=January 16, 2018 | accessdate=February 13, 2018}}</ref> has been recorded by more than 200 artists, and his \"[[This Masquerade]]\" by more than 75.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.musicrow.com/2017/01/nashville-related-music-obituaries-2016/ | title=Nashville-Related Music Obituaries 2016 | magazine=[[MusicRow]] | date=January 4, 2017 | accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/stories/leon-russell-remembered/|title=So Many Places: The Life Of Leon Russell|first=Richard|last=Havers|date=November 13, 2018|website=Udiscovermusic.com}}</ref><ref>Book: Graff, Gary, and Daniel Durchholz, MusicHound Rock: The Essential Album Guide, Visible Ink Press, 1999.</ref>\n\nAs a pianist, he played in his early years on albums by [[The Beach Boys]], [[Dick Dale]] and [[Jan and Dean]]. On his first album, [[Leon Russell (album)|''Leon Russell'']], in 1970, the musicians included [[Eric Clapton]], [[Ringo Starr]], and [[George Harrison]]. One of his biggest early fans,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.rickmcgrath.com/eltonjohn.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226154711/http://www.rickmcgrath.com/eltonjohn.html | title=This Is Your Song: The Elton John Interview | newspaper=[[The Georgia Straight]] | date=April 11, 1971 | archive-date=December 26, 2012 | accessdate=March 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://theoklahoma100.com/history/2016/05/18/oklahoma-rock-legend-leon-russell | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160904015032/http://theoklahoma100.com/history/2016/05/18/oklahoma-rock-legend-leon-russell | title=Oklahoma Rock Legend: Leon Russell | website=TheOklahoma100.com | date=May 18, 2016 | archive-date=September 4, 2016 | url-status=live | accessdate=March 14, 2020}}<!-- Contains rare early photo of Leon w/Elton. --></ref> [[Elton John]], said Russell was a \"mentor\" and an \"inspiration\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eltonjohn.com/stories/in-honor-of-leon-russell-1942-2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127055511/https://www.eltonjohn.com/stories/in-honor-of-leon-russell-1942-2016 | title=In Honor of Leon Russell (1942-2016) | website=EltonJohn.com | date=November 17, 2016 | archive-date=January 27, 2020 | url-status=live | accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> They recorded their album ''[[The Union (Elton John and Leon Russell album)|The Union]]'' in 2010,<ref name=\"somethingelsereviews.com\">[http://somethingelsereviews.com/2015/10/20/elton-john-leon-russell-the-union/ \"Elton John and Leon Russell's The Union Was Marked by This Bittersweet Sense of Loss\"]. ''Something Else Reviews'', October 20, 2015.</ref> which earned them a Grammy nomination.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/la-et-env-grammys-nominees-2010-list-htmlstory.html | title=Grammy Awards 2011: Winners and nominees for 53rd Grammy Awards | newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] | accessdate=March 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRussell produced and played in recording sessions for, among others [[Bob Dylan]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Ike & Tina Turner]], and [[The Rolling Stones]]. He wrote and recorded the hits \"[[Tight Rope (song)|Tight Rope]]\" and \"[[Lady Blue (song)|Lady Blue]]\". He performed at [[The Concert for Bangladesh]] in 1971 along with Harrison, Dylan, and Clapton, for which he earned a Grammy Award.\n\nHis recordings earned six [[Music recording certification|gold record]]s. He received two [[Grammy awards]] from seven nominations. In 2011, he was inducted into both the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] and the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.biography.com/people/leon-russell | title=Leon Russell Biography | website=Biography.com | accessdate=March 14, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422202336/http://www.biography.com/people/leon-russell | archive-date=April 22, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nRussell was born in [[Lawton, Oklahoma]],<ref name=\"NYT-2016\">{{cite news | last1=Pareles | first1=John | title=Leon Russell, Hit Maker and Musicians' Musician, Dies at 74 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/14/arts/music/leon-russell-hit-maker-and-musicians-musician-dies-at-74.html?_r=0 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> and began playing the piano at the age of four.\n\nRussell attended [[Will Rogers High School]] in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], alongside [[Anita Bryant]], who was two years older, and in the same 1959 class as pop musician [[David Gates]]. Russell and Gates played and recorded together as the Fencemen.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://beat-magazine.co.uk/2013/jfs-memory-time-machine-leon-russel |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221013624/http://beat-magazine.co.uk/2013/jfs-memory-time-machine-leon-russel |archive-date=December 21, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Also attending Will Rogers at that time was guitarist and singer-songwriter [[Elvin Bishop]]. During this time, Russell was already performing at Tulsa nightclubs. He took the name Leon from a friend who lent him a fake ID to get into clubs he was legally too young to perform in.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.leonrussellrecords.com/memory_lane.shtml | title=Leon Russell | website=Leonrussellrecords.com | accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter moving to Los Angeles in 1958, Russell became a [[session musician]], working as a pianist on the recordings of many notable 1960s musical artists. By the late 1960s, he had diversified, becoming successful as an arranger<ref>''Billboard '', September 18, 1965. p. 76.</ref> and songwriter. By 1970, he had become a solo recording artist, but he never relinquished his other roles in the music industry. Leon was a multi-instrumentalist playing: piano, keyboards, bass guitar, guitar, [[harpsichord]] and [[baritone horn]].\n\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|bgcolor = MistyRose|quote=I wanted to give Elton something. But what do you give a guy who has six fully stocked houses? So I thought the only thing I could give him is a song. \"In the Hands of Angels,\" retelling of the story of the album [''The Union''], thanks Mr. John (\"the guv'ner\" in the lyrics), who knew all the places I needed to go and made me feel the love down deep inside.|source=Leon Russell<ref name=NYT-2010/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GRdcl1dEG78 | title=Elton John and Leon Russell \u2013 The Hands of Angels (HQ) | date=October 12, 2010 | publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>}}\n\nRussell re-emerged in 2010 when [[Elton John]] called on him to record the album that became ''The Union''. The album, which included contributions from [[Brian Wilson]] and [[Neil Young]],<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7jb3aHQ7hjs | title=Roll Over Beethoven \u2013 Leon Russell (11/18/1964) HQ | date=February 11, 2011 | publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> brought renewed popularity to Russell, who later released a solo album and toured around the world.<ref>{{cite web | last=Hynes | first=Eric | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/leon-russell-on-his-lost-docs-long-strange-trip-20150702 | title=Leon Russell on His Lost Doc's Long, Strange Trip | work=Rolling Stone | date=July 2, 2015 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>Fong-Torres, Ben (1970). \"Leon Russell: The Rolling Stone Interview\". ''Rolling Stone'', December 2, 1970. pp. 32\u201338.</ref><ref>Laredo, Joseph F. (1996). \"The Master of Time & Space.\" Liner notes for ''Gimme Shelter! The Best of Leon Russell''. EMI/Shelter Records.</ref><ref>Simmons, Michael (2010). \"The Ringleader of Seventies Rock Royalty Returns from the Wilderness\". ''Mojo'', November 2010.</ref><ref>Roeser, Steve (1998). \"Leon Russell: Legend in His Time\". ''Goldmine'', September 11, 1998. pp. 26\u201344.</ref>\n\nRussell was inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] on March 14, 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://rockhall.com/inductees/leon-russell/ | title=Leon Russell: inducted in 2011 &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum | website=Rockhall.com | accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in June 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/C6041 | title=Leon Russell Exhibit Home | publisher=Songwriters Hall of Fame | accessdate=December 14, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115181743/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/C6041 | archive-date=November 15, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAccording to his wife, Jan Bridges, Russell died quietly in his sleep at his suburban Nashville home on the morning of November 13, 2016, at the age of 74.<ref>{{cite news | title=Leon Russell, Musician Known for Dynamic Performances, Dies at 74 | author=Trott, Bill | work=Reuters | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-leonrussell-idUSKBN1380JM  | date=November 13, 2016 | accessdate=November 13, 2016}}</ref> He had had a heart attack the previous July, followed by coronary bypass surgery, after which he postponed shows while convalescing at home. He had hoped to return to his concert schedule in January 2017.<ref name=Forbes>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/markbeech/2016/11/13/musicians-musician-rocker-leon-russell-dies-at-74/#2efd47966fe4 \"Musicians' Musician, Rocker Leon Russell, Dies at 74\"]. ''Forbes'', Nov. 13, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1950s/1960s===\nRussell began his musical career at the age of 14, in 1956, in the nightclubs of Tulsa, Oklahoma. He and his group, the Starlighters, which included [[J. J. Cale]], Leo Feathers, Chuck Blackwell, and Johnny Williams,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.willrogers1959.com/files/John_Williams_article_3-31-02.pdf | format=PDF | title=Come blow your horn | website=Willrogers1959.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> were instrumental in creating the style of music known as the [[Tulsa Sound]]. After settling in Los Angeles in 1958, he studied guitar with [[James Burton]]. He was known mostly as a session musician early in his career. As Russell developed his solo artist career he crossed genres to include [[rock and roll]], [[blues]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]] and [[gospel music]]. As a session musician he has played for and with artists as varied as [[Jan and Dean]], [[Gary Lewis & the Playboys]], [[George Harrison]], [[Delaney Bramlett]], [[Freddy Cannon]], [[Ringo Starr]], [[Doris Day]], Elton John, [[Ray Charles]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[The Byrds]], [[Barbra Streisand]], [[The Beach Boys]], [[The Ventures]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Badfinger]], the [[Herb Alpert|Tijuana Brass]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[The Band]], [[Bob Dylan]], J. J. Cale, [[B.B. King]],<ref>Liner notes. B. B. King, ''Indianola Mississippi Seeds''. ABC Dunhill Records.</ref> [[Dave Mason]], [[Glen Campbell]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[The Rolling Stones]], and [[The Flying Burrito Brothers]].<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\">{{cite book | author=Martin C. Strong | year=2000 | title=The Great Rock Discography | edition=5th | publisher=Mojo Books | location=Edinburgh | pages=838\u2013839 | isbn=1-84195-017-3}}</ref>\n\nIn Los Angeles, Russell played as a first-call studio musician on many of the most popular songs of the 1960s, including some by The Byrds, [[Gary Lewis & the Playboys]], [[Bobby Pickett]], and [[Herb Alpert]]. He also played piano on many [[Phil Spector]] productions, including recordings by [[The Ronettes]], [[The Crystals]], and [[Darlene Love]] and in the 1963 ''[[A Christmas Gift for You from Phil Spector]]'' album. He can be seen in the 1964 concert film ''[[T.A.M.I. Show]]'' playing piano with [[The Wrecking Crew (music)|The Wrecking Crew]] (an informal name for the top Los Angeles session musicians of the 1960s), sporting short, dark, slicked-back hair, in contrast to his later look.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> Soon after, he was hired as [[Snuff Garrett]]'s assistant and creative developer, playing on numerous number-one singles, including \"[[This Diamond Ring]]\" by Gary Lewis & the Playboys.<ref>''Billboard'', March 4, 1967, and December 15, 1973, p. 37.</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1960s, he wrote or co-wrote songs, including two hits for Gary Lewis and the Playboys: \"[[Everybody Loves a Clown (song)|Everybody Loves a Clown]]\" (which reached the ''Billboard'' Top 40 on October 9, 1965, remaining on the chart for eight weeks and reaching number 4) and \"[[She's Just My Style]]\" (which entered the ''Billboard'' Top 40 on December 18, 1965, and rose to number 3).<ref>See Whitburn, Joel (1992). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits''. 5th ed. Billboard Books. p. 275. {{ISBN|978-0823082803}}.</ref> In 1964, he appeared on various TV shows, performing songs by [[Chuck Berry]] and others.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nHe played xylophone and bells on the 1966 single \"The Joker Went Wild\", sung by [[Brian Hyland]] and written by [[Bobby Russell]] (no relation to Leon). He also contributed to recording sessions with [[Dorsey Burnette]] and with Glen Campbell, whose 1967 album ''[[Gentle on My Mind (1967 Glen Campbell album)|Gentle on My Mind]]'' credited him as \"Russell Bridges\" on piano,<ref>{{cite web | author=Joe Marchese | url=http://theseconddisc.com/2011/06/24/gentle-on-his-mind-two-early-glen-campbell-classics-reissued-by-bgo/ | title=Gentle on His Mind: Two Early Glen Campbell Classics Reissued by BGO | publisher=The Second Disc | date=June 24, 2011 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> and arranged and conducted the 1966 [[easy listening]] album ''Rhapsodies for Young Lovers'' by the [[Midnight String Quartet]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/rhapsodies-for-young-lovers-mw0000497944/credits | title=Rhapsodies for Young Lovers \u2013 Midnight String Quartet &#124; Credits | website=[[AllMusic]] | date=October 16, 2007 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> He co-produced and arranged hits by [[Tom Northcott]], including \"Sunny Goodge Street\" in 1967, written by [[Donovan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/sunny-goodge-street-mw0002303572 | title=AllMusic Review | author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref>\n\nRussell released his first solo single, \"Everybody's Talking 'Bout the Young\", for Dot Records in 1965.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://rockhall.com/inductees/leon-russell/bio/#sthash.N5M9ExyT.dpuf | title=Leon Russell Biography &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum | website=Rockhall.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe 1968 release of ''[[Look Inside the Asylum Choir]]'' by Smash Records was a recording of a studio group consisting of Russell and [[Marc Benno]] (\"[[The Asylum Choir]]\").<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/look-inside-the-asylum-choir-r172393 | title=Look Inside the Asylum Choir \u2013 The Asylum Choir &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell and [[Denny Cordell]] established [[Shelter Records]] in 1969. The company operated from 1969 to 1981, with offices in Los Angeles and Tulsa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.discogs.com/label/44717-Shelter-Records | title=Shelter Records: CDs and Vinyl | website=Discogs.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> Shelter used [[Sound City Studios]] for recording in its early days.<ref name=\"NYT-2016\"/>\n\nRussell performed as a member of [[Delaney & Bonnie|Delaney & Bonnie and Friends]] in 1969 and 1970, playing guitar and keyboards on their albums and as part of the touring band. Through this group, he met [[George Harrison]] and others with whom he would work over the next couple of years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/delaneyandbonnie.html | title=Delaney and Bonnie: A History of Their Music | website=Furious.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell's first commercial success as a songwriter came when Joe Cocker recorded the song \"Delta Lady\" for his 1969 album, ''[[Joe Cocker!]]''<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> The album, co-produced and arranged by Russell, reached number 11 on the ''Billboard'' 200.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/joe-cocker-r4236/charts-awards | title=Joe Cocker! \u2013 Joe Cocker | website=AllMusic | accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> Russell went on to organize and perform in (playing either piano or lead guitar) the 1970 ''[[Mad Dogs and Englishmen (album)|Mad Dogs and Englishmen]]'' tour, using many of the musicians from Delaney and Bonnie's band.<ref>[http://www.lindawolf.net/Joe ] {{webarchive | url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723182520/http://www.lindawolf.net/Joe | date=July 23, 2011}}</ref> \"[[Superstar (Delaney and Bonnie song)#Mad Dogs and Englishmen version|Superstar]]\", co-written by Russell, was sung by [[The Carpenters]] and other performers.<ref name=\"NYT-2016\"/>\n\n===1970s===\nDuring the ''Mad Dogs and Englishmen'' tour, Shelter Records released his 1970 solo album, ''[[Leon Russell (album)|Leon Russell]]'', which included the first recording of \"[[A Song for You]]\". This has become one of his best-known songs, with versions released by more than 40 different artists, including [[The Carpenters]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Billy Eckstine]], [[Peggy Lee]], [[Willie Nelson]], [[Helen Reddy]], [[Carmen McRae]], [[Elkie Brooks]], [[Freda Payne]], and [[Donny Hathaway]]. Both The Carpenters and [[The Temptations]] named an album after the song. Another song from the same album, \"Delta Lady\", was covered by [[Bobbie Gentry]] under the title \"Delta Man\" on her 1970 album ''[[Fancy (Bobbie Gentry album)|Fancy]]''.  Leon Russell album had a number of guest vocalist and accompaniment: [[Chris Stainton]], [[Bonnie Bramlett]], Greg Dempsey, [[Bob Dylan]], [[Marc Benno]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Mick Jagger]], [[Keith Richards]], [[George Harrison]], [[Ringo Starr]], Joe Cocker, and [[Merry Clayton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/leon-russell-mw0000392176/credits|title=Leon Russell \u2013 Leon Russell \u2013 Credits|website=AllMusic}}</ref> Leon Russell's ''A Song For You'' was added to Grammy Hall Of Fame for the 2018 Grammy Hall of Fame class.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/5579892/leon-russells-a-song-for-you-added-to-grammy-hall-of-fame/|title=Leon Russell's 'A Song For You' added to Grammy Hall Of Fame|date=January 17, 2018|website=NewsOK.com}}</ref><ref>[https://www.tulsaworld.com/entertainment/pop-culture-leon-russell-song-selected-for-grammy-hall-of/article_a4b06b88-3f54-5543-9295-cfa69c92c655.html Tulsaworld.com,  Pop culture: Leon Russell song selected for Grammy Hall of Fame, By Jimmie Tramel, Jan. 18, 2018]</ref>\n\nAlso in 1970, Russell played piano on [[Dave Mason]]'s album ''[[Alone Together (Dave Mason album)|Alone Together]]'', notably on the song \"Sad and Deep as You\".<ref>''The Encyclopedia of Country Music'', 2012: \"In 1970 Russell released his self-titled debut solo album, including such enduring songs as 'Delta Lady' and 'A Song for You,' both written for versatile vocalist Rita Coolidge. He followed with Leon Russell and the Shelter People (1971) and ...\"</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/composition/dafcda8b-3846-4392-a07c-f51adeb78609-A-Song-For-You|title=A Song For You|website=Discogs|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p3159|pure_url=yes}} |title=''Billboard'' Singles|publisher=[[All Media Guide]] / [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=2010-03-01}}</ref> [[Ray Charles]] recorded a version that earned him the 1994 [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/blogs/scene/popculture/pop-culture-leon-russell-song-selected-for-grammy-hall-of/article_a4b06b88-3f54-5543-9295-cfa69c92c655.html|title=Pop culture: Leon Russell song selected for Grammy Hall of Fame|first=Jimmie Tramel Tulsa|last=World|website=Tulsa World}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.concertarchives.org/concerts/leon-russell-elton-john-mckendree-spring|title=11/21/1970: Leon Russell / Elton John / McKendree Spring @ Fillmore East \u2013 Concert Archives|website=Concertarchives.org}}</ref> The song ''The Letter'' by Joe Cocker with Leon Russell & The Shelter \n\nPeople peaked at #7 on the Hot 100 on May 30, 1970 this is Leon first hit song.<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/leon-russell|title=Leon Russell Chart History|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn November 1970, Russell performed at the Fillmore East with Elton John on the same bill. Those performances have been bootlegged. Russell and John appeared on ''The David Frost Show'' with Fillmore owner Bill Graham at this time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thefatangelsings.com/2016/11/20/leon-russell-live-at-the-fillmore-east-24th-november-1970/|title=LEON RUSSELL \u2013 \u201d Live At The Fillmore East \u201d 20th November 1970|date=November 20, 2016|website=Thefatangelsings.com}}</ref>\n\n\"Leon Russell and Friends\" recorded the \"Homewood Sessions\", broadcast as an \"unscripted and unrehearsed\" one-hour TV special on [[KCET]] (Los Angeles) that aired in December 1970 and was later re-broadcast several times on the [[Public Broadcasting Service]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bigozine3.com/cdcvrsB/images205B/LRhwooddvd/LRhwooddvd.pdf | format=PDF | title=Leon Russell and Friends | year=1971 | website=Bigozine3.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nLeon performed on [[The David Frost Show]] on December 3, 1970.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/shows/the-david-frost-show/december-3-1970-1274663/ The David Frost Show Season 3 Episode 49, December 3, 1970]</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s and 1980s, Russell owned [[The Church Studio]] on 3rd Street (renamed Leon Russell Road in 2010 by the Pearl District Association) in Tulsa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thislandpress.com/05/09/2012/the-making-of-leon-russell-road/?page_num=1 | title=Made by You and Me \u2013 The Making of Leon Russell Road | publisher=This Land Press | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> His former home on Grand Lake, in Oklahoma, contained a dining room table and chairs made from church pews taken out of the church when it was turned into a studio.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.travelok.com/rhythm-and-routes/venues/the-church-studio | title=Oklahoma Music Trail: The Church Studio | website=TravelOK.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis album ''Prince of Peace: Radio Broadcast 1970'' is a [[soundboard recording]] of a concert at Fillmore East in December 1970.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/prince-of-peace-radio-broadcast-1970-mw0002850801 | title=Prince of Peace: Radio Broadcast 1970 \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | date=August 14, 2015 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell produced some tracks for Bob Dylan in March 1971 when Dylan was experimenting with his new sound. The sessions produced the single \"[[Watching the River Flow]]\" and \"[[When I Paint My Masterpiece]]\", both of which prominently featured Russell's gospel-flavored piano.<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/watching-the-river-flow-mt0032662306 | title=Watching the River Flow \u2013 Bob Dylan &#124; Song Info | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the invitation of former Delaney & Bonnie and George Harrison, Russell played piano on [[Badfinger]]'s third album, ''[[Straight Up (Badfinger album)|Straight Up]]'' in the summer of 1971. The piano part complemented Pete Ham's and George Harrison's dual slide guitars on Badfinger's \"[[Day After Day (Badfinger song)|Day After Day]]\". The ''Straight Up'' sessions were interrupted when many of the musicians left for New York City to participate in [[The Concert for Bangladesh]], at which Russell performed a medley of the songs \"[[Jumpin' Jack Flash]]\" and \"[[Young Blood (The Coasters song)|Young Blood]]\" and sang a verse on Harrison's \"[[Beware of Darkness (song)|Beware of Darkness]]\". Leon performed piano, vocals, bass and backing vocals at the Concert on 1 August 1971. ''[[The Concert for Bangladesh (album)|The Concert for Bangladesh]]'' album released in 1971 was a major critical and commercial success. The album topped albums charts in several countries and went on to win the [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year]] in March 1973. The Concert also became an [[The Concert for Bangladesh (film)|Apple concert film]] directed by [[Saul Swimmer]].<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Various-The-Concert-For-Bangla-Desh/release/559574 discogs.com, The Concert for Bangladesh]</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0158560/ imdb.com, The Concert for Bangladesh]</ref><ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/concert-for-bangladesh-248989/ rollingstone.com, Concert For Bangladesh, by Jon Landau, February 3, 1972]</ref>\nBob Dylan surprised Russell by asking him to play bass for some of Dylan's portion of the Concert; Russell and Harrison sang harmonies on the chorus of \"[[Just Like a Woman]]\".<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/>\n\nRussell was busy in 1971, as Shelter Records released ''[[Leon Russell and the Shelter People]]'' and ''[[Asylum Choir II]]'' (co-produced by Marc Benno) and recorded at Russell's Skyhill Studios. ''Leon Russell and the Shelter People'' went on to be Russell's first U.S. gold album. In the same year, Russell played on recording sessions with B. B. King, Eric Clapton, and Bob Dylan.<ref name=\"NYT-2016\"/><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2016/11/13/leon-russell-has-died-74-obituary/93763740/ \"Musician Leon Russell Has Died at 74\"]. ''USA Today'', November 13, 2016.</ref>\n[[File:Leon Russell 1970s.jpg|thumb|right|Russell in 1970]]\n\nRussell helped the blues guitarist [[Freddie King]] revive his career by collaborating on three of King's albums for Shelter Records during the early 1970s. During those same years, Russell profited from what was then called the \"country and western\" market by recording and performing under the moniker \"Hank Wilson\",<ref>{{cite web | author=Thom Jurek | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/best-of-hank-wilson-mw0000819188 | title=Best of Hank Wilson \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards | website=AllMusic | date=June 23, 2009 | accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> and was a regular performer at [[Gilley's Club]], a honkytonk in [[Pasadena, Texas]] made famous by the film ''[[Urban Cowboy]]''.<ref>Billboard Aug 18, 1979, page TO-4</ref>\n\nRussell recorded the song \"Get a Line on You\" at [[Olympic Studios]] in October 1969, with contributions from Mick Jagger (lead vocal), Ringo Starr (drums), and probably also [[Bill Wyman]] (bass) and [[Mick Taylor]] (guitar). The recording was made during the recording sessions for the album ''Leon Russell'' (released in 1970), for which Starr and Wyman played drums and bass on some tracks, but was not included on the album. It was shelved until 1993, when it was issued as a bonus track on the 24K gold re-release by DCC Compact Classics (DCC Compact Classics GZS 1049). The Rolling Stones included the song, under the title \"[[Shine a Light (The Rolling Stones song)|Shine a Light]]\" on their 1972 album ''[[Exile on Main St.]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nzentgraf.de/books/tcw/works1.htm | title=The Complete Works of the Rolling Stones \u2013 Database | website=Nzentgraf.de | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell and his band hit the road in 1972 with a large-scale concert tour by Russell and his \"Shelter People\" entourage. A live performance was recorded in California at the [[Long Beach Arena]] on August 28, 1972,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Leon-Live/release/468749 | title=Leon Russell \u2013 Leon Live (Vinyl, LP, Album) | website=Discogs.com | date=August 28, 1972 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> and was released as a three-record set in 1973 as ''[[Leon Live]]''. It became his third U.S. gold album. In November 1972, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' cited Russell as a top concert draw and reported the 1972 tour gross at almost $3 million.<ref name=\"Softshoe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.softshoe-slim.com/lists/r/russell_leon.html|title=Leon Russell Albums|website=Softshoe-slim.com|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>[''Billboard'' vol. 84, no. 45, p. 40, November 4, 1972.]</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web|url=https://api.discogs.com/artists/255183|title=Leon Russell|website=Discogs|accessdate=April 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 1972, he released his [[Carney (Leon Russell album)|''Carney'']] album, which was his third solo studio album. The album peaked at number two on the Billboard 200. The album featured \"[[Tight Rope (song)|Tight Rope]]\" and \"[[This Masquerade]]\" (songs released on a 45 as the A side and B side respectively), and became his second gold album.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d2Z9qN8R9Bg | title=Tight Rope / Leon Russell | date=March 2, 2008 | publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nRussell purchased multiple properties in the early 1970s in his home state of Oklahoma, including the historic [[The Church Studio]] in 1972 located on the corner of 3rd Street and Trenton in Tulsa, Oklahoma. The church was also home to Shelter Records. Numerous musicians recorded at The Church, including [[Willie Nelson]], [[Eric Clapton]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Dwight Twilley]], [[Dr. John]], [[JJ Cale]], [[The Gap Band]], [[Freddie King]], [[Phoebe Snow]] and [[Peter Tosh]]. [[Tom Petty]], with his early band [[Mudcrutch]], signed his first record deal with Shelter Records there.<ref>Julie Wenger Watson, [http://nodepression.com/article/leon-russell-has-home-sweet-oklahoma-his-mind \"Leon Russell Has Home Sweet Oklahoma on his Mind\"], ''[[No Depression (magazine)|No Depression]]'', July 28, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20170915.htm|title=Weekly List \u2013 National Register of Historic Places Official Website\u2014Part of the National Park Service|website=Nps.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.route66news.com/tag/church-studio/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229220407/https://www.route66news.com/tag/church-studio/ |archive-date=December 29, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelok.com/rhythm-and-routes/venues/the-church-studio|title=Oklahoma Music Trail: The Church Studio|website=TravelOK.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsapeople.com/Tulsa-People/September-2013/A-sanctuary-of-sound/|title=A sanctuary of sound |website=TulsaPeople.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/60231/conversations-with-tom-petty|title=Conversations With Tom Petty|website=Billboard.com}}</ref><ref>Paul Zollo, [https://americansongwriter.com/2005/11/the-purity-and-passion-of-tom-petty/5/ \"Tom Petty: Purity and Passion\"], ''[[American Songwriter]]'', November 1, 2005.</ref>\n\n''[[Looking Back (Leon Russell album)|Looking Back]]'' was released by Russell on Olympia Records in 1973, shortly after the success of his single \"Tight Rope\". It contains instrumental tracks recorded in the mid-1960s, featuring Russell playing the harpsichord.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Looking-Back/release/4255583|title=Leon Russell \u2013 Looking Back|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\nRussell released the album ''[[Hank Wilson's Back Vol. I]]'', which was recorded at producer [[Owen Bradley]]'s barn studio in Nashville in 1973. The album made it into the Top Thirty Hits. Track one, \"[[Roll in My Sweet Baby's Arms]]\", was a minor hit.<ref name=\"rockhall1\"/><ref>{{cite web | author=Thom Jurek | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hank-wilsons-back!-mw0000207368 | title=Hank Wilson's Back! \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Hank-Wilsons-Back-Vol-I/master/447060 | title=Leon Russell \u2013 Hank Wilson's Back Vol. I}}</ref>\n\nRussell helped the [[Gap Band]], a trio of Tulsa brothers,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-gap-band-mn0000073383/biography | title=The Gap Band {{!}} Biography & History {{!}} AllMusic | website=AllMusic | accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref> kick off their chart success in 1974. The group went on to produce several funk-disco hits.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Gap Band backed Russell on his album ''[[Stop All That Jazz]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/stop-all-that-jazz-mw0000207825 | title=Stop All That Jazz \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released ''[[Live in Japan (Leon Russell album)|Live In Japan]]'' on Shelter Records. The album was recorded live at Budokan Hall, in Tokyo, on November 8, 1973, and released in 1975.<ref>{{cite web | author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-in-japan-mw0000848894 | title=Live in Japan \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=[[AllMusic]] | date=April 22, 1971 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell made it into the 1975 [[Top 40]] with \"Lady Blue\", from his album ''[[Will O' the Wisp (album)|Will o' the Wisp]]''. It was his fourth gold album.<ref name=\"rockhall1\">{{cite web | url=https://rockhall.com/inductees/leon-russell/bio/#sthash.3kBNPQY8.dpuf | title=Leon Russell Biography &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum | website=Rockhall.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHelen Reddy recorded Russell's song \"Bluebird\" as a single and on her 1975 album ''[[No Way to Treat a Lady (album)|No Way to Treat a Lady]]''.<ref name=\"collection\">(2006) CD booklet with Helen Reddy, ''The Woman I Am: The Definitive Collection''. Los Angeles: Capitol Records 09463-57613-2-0.</ref> The song debuted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] in the July 5th issue of the magazine and eventually peaked at number 35.<ref name=\"hot\">{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2009|p=805}} {{which|date=December 2015}}</ref> That same issue also marked its debut on the magazine's [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]] chart, where it spent eight weeks and peaked at number 5;<ref name=\"adult\">{{Harvnb|Whitburn|2007|p=226}} {{which|date=December 2015}}</ref> on the ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' singles chart it reached number 51.<ref>{{cite news | title=RPM Top Singles | date=August 16, 1975 | work=RPM | page=26}}</ref> Reddy said, \"I love Leon Russell's writing and I love this song. It was an integral part of my repertoire for nearly 30 years, and I never tired of singing it.\"<ref name=\"collection\"/>\n\nRussell's song \"This Masquerade\", the B-side of his 1972 hit single \"Tight Rope\", was later recorded by numerous artists, including Helen Reddy and The Carpenters. [[George Benson]]'s version of the song reached number 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] at the [[1977 Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/search/track/This+Masquerade/order:year-asc | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718105051/http://www.allmusic.com/search/track/This%2BMasquerade/order%3Ayear-asc | url-status=dead | archive-date=July 18, 2011 | title=Music Search, Recommendations, Videos and Reviews | website=AllMusic | accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> As the song writer, Russell was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] in 1977 but lost to Bruce Johnston, who wrote \"[[I Write the Songs]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1977-225.html | title=Grammy Awards 1977  | website=Awardsandshows.com | accessdate=November 14, 2016 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207110610/http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/grammy-awards-1977-225.html | archivedate=December 7, 2016 | df=mdy-all}}</ref> Russell's version of \"This Masquerade\" was used for the soundtrack for the psychological thriller film ''[[Bug (2007 film)|Bug]]'', which was directed by [[William Friedkin]]. The [[Bug (2007 soundtrack)|''Bug'' soundtrack]] was released on May 22, 2007. The song was also used in the movie ''[[The Pursuit of Happyness]]''.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0470705/soundtrack imdb.com, Bug (2007 film)]</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0454921/soundtrack imdb.com, The Pursuit of Happyness]</ref>\n\nRussell departed Shelter Records in 1976 to start his own record label, [[Paradise Records]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.discogs.com/label/107875-Paradise-Records-8?sort=year&sort_order=asc | title=Paradise Records (8) \u2013 CDs and Vinyl | website=Discogs.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976 Leon and Barbra Streisand wrote the song \"Lost Inside of You\" for the film sound track of ''[[A Star Is Born (1976 soundtrack)|A Star Is Born]]''. Barbra Streisand and [[Kris Kristofferson]] performed the song. The ''A Star Is Born'' soundtrack received a [[20th Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Nominations]] for Best Album of Original Score written for a Motion Picture or Television Special.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075265/awards imdb.com, A Star Is Born (1976), Awards]</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Russell released the ''[[Wedding Album (Leon and Mary Russell album)|Wedding Album]]'', a studio album with his then wife, Mary Russell,<ref name=\"allmusic.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wedding-album-mw0000488704 | title=Leon Russell / Leon & Mary Russell \u2013 ''Wedding Album'' | website=AllMusic | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> otherwise known as [[Little Sister (band)|Mary McCreary]]. It was the first release by Paradise Records, and it was distributed by Rhino/[[Warner Bros. Records]].<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/wedding-album-mw0000488704/releases allmusic.com, Wedding Album, releases]</ref> Leon and Mary were the album producers, except for the final track \"Daylight\", which was produced by its writer [[Bobby Womack]].<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/wedding-album-mw0000488704/credits allmusic.com, Wedding Album, Credits]</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 1976 Leon and Mary performed \"[[Wedding Album (Leon and Mary Russell album)|Satisfy You]]\" and \"[[Daylight (Bobby Womack song)|Daylight]]\" with [[John Belushi]] as Joe Cocker on [[Saturday Night Live]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0694444/plotsummary?ref_=tt_ov_pl imdb.com, Saturday Night Live, May 15, 1976]</ref>\n\n''[[Make Love to the Music]]'' is the second album by Leon & Mary Russell released in 1977 on Paradise Records.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/make-love-to-the-music-mw0000489942 allmusic.com, Make Love to the Music]</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Russell released his ''[[Americana (Leon Russell album)|Americana]]'' album on the Rhino/Warner Bros. label.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/americana-mw0000489941 | title=Leon Russell \u2013 ''Americana'' | website=AllMusic | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter touring with Willie Nelson, Russell and Nelson in 1979 had a #1 hit on ''Billboard''s [[country music]] chart with their duet of \"[[Heartbreak Hotel]]\". This single was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Country Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Country Vocal Performance by a Duo or Group]] at the [[22nd Annual Grammy Awards|1979 Grammy Awards]]<ref name=\"Grammy history\">{{cite web | url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/leon-russell | title=Artist Leon Russell: Grammy Award History | publisher=[[The Recording Academy]] | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> (presented on February 27, 1980), with the award going to the [[Charlie Daniels|Charlie Daniels Band]] for \"[[The Devil Went Down to Georgia]]\". They also released their duet country pop-rock studio album, ''[[One for the Road (Willie Nelson and Leon Russell album)|One for the Road]]'', that year. It was Russell's fifth gold album.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> The album was nominated for 1979's Album of the Year awarded by the [[Country Music Association]], which went to [[Kenny Rogers]] for ''[[The Gambler (album)|The Gambler]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cmaworld.com/cma-awards/past-winners/ | title=Past CMA Awards Winners and Nominees: Searchable CMA Awards Database \u2013 Leon Russell | publisher=[[Country Music Association]] | accessdate=August 12, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709135030/http://www.cmaworld.com/cma-awards/past-winners/ | archive-date=July 9, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The track \"[[I Saw the Light (Hank Williams song)|I Saw the Light]]\" was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Inspirational Performance|Best Inspirational Performance]] at the 1979 Grammy Awards,<ref name=\"Grammy history\"/> which instead went to [[B. J. Thomas]] for his album ''[[You Gave Me Love (When Nobody Gave Me a Prayer)|You Gave Me Love (When Nobody Gave Me A Prayer)]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/22nd-annual-grammy-awards | title=WINNERS: 22nd Annual GRAMMY Awards (1979) | publisher=[[The Recording Academy]] | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeon built and owned Paradise Studios in [[Burbank, California]]; the [[recording studio]] had two audio [[sound stage]]s and one [[Television studio|television production stage]]. The studios complex also had a mobile audio recording bus and [[Outside broadcasting|remote television production bus]] that supported the stages or could travel. Paradise Records was also headquartered at the studio. The studio aired a weekly [[live television]] music show ''[[New Wave Theatre]]'' shown on [[USA network]]. The studio was used to make music videos from [[James Taylor]] and [[Randy Meisner]], also long format video for Willie Nelson, [[J.J.Cale]], [[Bonnie Raitt]] and Leon Russell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/604814-Paradise-Studios-Hollywood|title=Paradise Studios, Hollywood|website=Discogs}}</ref>\n\nRussell released ''[[Life and Love (Leon Russell album)|Life And Love]]'', an album on Paradise Records, in 1979. ''Life and Love'' has country, rock blues songs that harked back to Leon's work in the early 1970.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/life-and-love-mw0000750356 | title=Life and Love \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===1980s===\nRussell spent 1980 and 1981  touring with the [[New Grass Revival]], releasing two more albums with Paradise Records before the label folded.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/>\n\nOn May 1, 1982 Leon played at [[Joe Ely]]'s Third Annual Tornado Jam in [[Lubbock, Texas]] to a crowd of 25,000. The Jam included [[Joan Jett]] and [[The Crickets]].<ref>[Billboard May 1, 1982, page 30</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 1980, Russell joined with [[New Grass Revival]] to record a live album at Perkins Palace in [[Pasadena, California]], released in 1981 as ''[[The Live Album (Leon Russell and New Grass Revival)]].<ref name=\"discogs.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-New-Grass-Revival-The-Live-Album/release/1776481 |title=Leon Russell & New Grass Revival \u2013 The Live Album (Vinyl, LP, Album) |website=Discogs.com |date=May 15, 1980 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982 Leon played piano and percussion on New Grass Revival 'a ''[[Commonwealth (New Grass Revival album)|Commonwealth]]'' album.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/commonwealth-mw0000310030/credits allmusic, Commonwealth]</ref>\n\nFollowing up on his country theme, he made a second Hank Wilson album, ''[[Hank Wilson, Vol. II]]''  released in 1984, Hank Wilson being Russell's self-styled country music alter-ego since the early 1970s. Released on Leon Russell Records.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Hank-Wilson-Vol-II/release/2351624 |title=Leon Russell \u2013 Hank Wilson Vol. II (Vinyl, LP, Album) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released a country blues album, recorded in Hendersonville, Tennessee, at his Paradise Studios, called ''[[Solid State (Leon Russell album)|Solid State]]''. It was released by Paradise Music in 1984.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Solid-State/release/2351637 |title=Leon Russell \u2013 Solid State (Vinyl, LP, Album) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 Leon went on tour, some of the cities were: January 25, 1985 at the [[Capitol Theatre (Passaic, New Jersey)|Capitol Theatre]], Passaic, NJ. On March 12, 1985 at [[Rainbow Music Hall]] n [[Denver]], [[Colorado]]. June 17, 1985 at [[Ritz-Carlton Hotel (New York City)|The Ritz]], New York, NY and on  September 19, 1985 at The Vogue in Indianapolis, IN.<ref>[https://www.setlist.fm/stats/concert-map/leon-russell-4bd64b2e.html?year=1985 Russell, Leon > Tour Statistics]</ref>\n\nIn 1985 Leon released the compilation album ''Best Of Leon Russell: A Song For You'', distributed By CBS/Sony .<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">[https://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Best-Of-Leon-Russell-A-Song-For-You/release/6946931 discogs.com ''Best Of Leon Russell: A Song For You'']</ref>\n\nIn 1988 and 1989 [[Edgar Winter]] and Leon Russell went on concert tour of the US and Canada. Edgar Winter is multi-instrumentalist, songwriter and record producer. In 2002 the DVD ''Edgar Winter \u2013 Live on Stage, Featuring Leon Russell'' was released.<ref>[LA Times, Double Bill Due at the Coach House: Leon Russell and Edgar Winter, Nov 9, 1988</ref><ref>[https://www.tulsaworld.com/archive/leon-russell-to-perform-here-with-edgar-winter/article_c3dd79a1-9bc7-55d0-8e97-a557187c57b8.html tulsaworld.com,  Leon Russell to Perform Here With Edgar Winter, by John Wooley, Sep 26, 1989]</ref><ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/edgar-winter-live-featuring-leon-russell-mw0000984846/releases allmusic.com ''Edgar Winter \u2013 Live on Stage, Featuring Leon Russell'']</ref>\n\n===1990s===\nRussell released ''Delta Lady'' on Del Rack Records in 1991. Many of the songs are remixes of early recordings.<ref name=\"forums.stevehoffman.tv\">{{cite web | url=http://forums.stevehoffman.tv/threads/leon-russell-delta-lady-on-del-rack-album-review.8417/ | title=Leon Russell \u2013 \"Delta Lady\" on Del Rack-ALBUM REVIEW &#124; Steve Hoffman Music Forums | website=Forums.stevehoffman.tv | date=November 13, 2002 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released a new album ''[[Anything Can Happen (Leon Russell album)|Anything Can Happen]]'' recorded at Paradise Studios, released on [[Virgin Records]] in 1991. Pianist [[Bruce Hornsby]] produced this comeback album. During the late 1980s and early 1990s Hornsby worked extensively as a producer and sideman with Russell.<ref name=\"Roch Parisien\">{{cite web|author=Roch Parisien |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/anything-can-happen-mw0000279640 |title=Anything Can Happen \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Paradise Records released the ''Leon Russell 24k Gold Disc'' album. It was a remix of recordings done at Olympic Sound in London in 1969.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-Leon-Russell/release/4285011 |title=Leon Russell \u2013 Leon Russell (CD, Album) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell started '''Leon Russell Records''', an [[independent record label]], in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leonrussellrecords.com/ |title=Leon Russell |website=Leonrussellrecords.com |date= |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released his  ''[[Hymns of Christmas]]'' Leon Russell: Piano and Orchestra, album with 10 instrumental hymns by Russell on Leon Russell Records in 1995.<ref name=\"Zac Johnson\">{{cite web|author=Zac Johnson |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hymns-of-christmas-mw0000591612 |title=Hymns of Christmas \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCapitol/EMI Records in 1996 released the album ''Gimme Shelter! The Best of Leon Russell'', a two-CD album set with 40-tracks covering 1969\u20131992.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Richie Unterberger]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/gimme-shelter!-the-best-of-leon-russell-mw0000176325 |title=Gimme Shelter!: The Best of Leon Russell \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nCapitol/Right Stuff Records released in 1997 the album ''Retrospective'', an album with Russell's 18 all-time best-selling songs.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/retrospective-mw0000690090 |title=Retrospective \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=[[AllMusic]] |date=October 21, 1997 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released a new album ''[[Legend in My Time: Hank Wilson Vol. III]]''. Returning to his county artist name on [[Ark 21 Records]], released in 1998 .<ref name=\"Matthew Greenwald\">{{cite web|author=Matthew Greenwald |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/hank-wilson-vol-3-legend-in-my-time-mw0000035717 |title=Hank Wilson, Vol. 3: Legend in My Time \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=April 7, 1998 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell released ''[[Face in the Crowd (Leon Russell album)|Face in the Crowd]]'' in 1999, a blues album on Sagestone Entertainment Records.<ref name=\"William Ruhlmann\">{{cite web|author=William Ruhlmann |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/face-in-the-crowd-mw0000047983 |title=Face in the Crowd \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=January 26, 1999 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"A Familiar Face in the Crowd\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/feb/17/entertainment/ca-8746 |title=A Familiar Face in the Crowd |website=Articles.latimes.com |date=February 17, 1999 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Blues: Same Old Song]]'' CD was released on Paradise Records in 1999.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/blues-same-old-song-mw0000541297 |title=Blues: Same Old Song \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=December 7, 1999 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\n[[File:Leon Russell in 2009.jpg|thumb|Russell in 2009]]\nIn 2000, Russell and Q Records released ''[[Live at Gilley's]]'', a performance from September 17, 1981 at [[Gilley's Club]].<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/live-at-gilleys-mw0000061141 | title=Live at Gilley's \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=AllMusic | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>  Also in 2000, Leon Russell Records released the rock album ''Crazy Love'' on CD.<ref name=\"Leon Russell Latest Albums\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/leon-russell/discography/ | title=Leon Russell Latest Albums | website=MTV.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 Leon teamed up with multi-instrumentalis Matt Harris to make Matt's album ''Slightly Elliptical Orbit''. Matt and Leon wrote 10 songs for the 12 track album. Leon sang on only one track ''This Train''. The album was released in 2002 on Leon Russell Records.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/slightly-elliptical-orbit-mw0000216502 Allmusic, ''Slightly Elliptical Orbit'']</ref><ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Matt-Harris-Leon-Russell-Slightly-Elliptical-Orbit/release/7323282 discogs.com, ''Slightly Elliptical Orbit'']</ref>\n\n'''''Signature Songs''''' was released in 2001 on Leon Russell Records. On the album Leon plays all his top songs from his long career. It was re-released in 2007 by MRI Associated Labels.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/signature-songs-mw0000590602 |title=Signature Songs \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=August 21, 2001 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell returned as Hank Wilson, but this time with a twist of bluegrass, in ''[[Rhythm & Bluegrass: Hank Wilson, Vol. 4]]'', released in 2001 on Leon Russell Records. The songs are with New Grass Revival from the 1980s.<ref name=\"Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr\">{{cite web|author=Ronnie D. Lankford, Jr. |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/rhythm-bluegrass-hank-wilson-vol-4-mw0000015899 |title=Rhythm & Bluegrass: Hank Wilson, Vol. 4 \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=October 23, 2001 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell and the others who played on the \"[[Foggy Mountain Breakdown]]\" track each won [[Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Country Instrumental Performance|Best Country Instrumental Performance]] at the [[44th Annual Grammy Awards|2001 Grammy Awards]],<ref name=\"Grammy history\"/> which were presented on February 27, 2002.\n\n''[[Moonlight & Love Songs]]'', an album Russell made with the [[Nashville Symphony]], was released on Leon Russell Records in 2002.<ref name=\"Chris Nickson\">{{cite web|author=Chris Nickson |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/moonlight-love-songs-mw0000659082 |title=Moonlight & Love Songs \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=April 9, 2002 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Leon release a 95 minutes DVD titled \"A Song for You\", that features 25 Russell classics songs from the Shelter People to 2001. There is biographical commentary throughout the DVD. The video is of both concerts and studio sessions.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/a-song-for-you-dvd-mw0001258152/releases allmusic.com, \"A Song for You\" DVD]</ref>\n\nIn 2002 Leon released the DVD album ''[[Live And Pickling Fast]]'', this was a  new album of the live Perkins Palace event on May 15, 1980. The new album has all the original songs from ''The Live Album (with New Grass Revival)'', plus all the other songs from the event.<ref name=\"ReferenceE\">[https://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-And-The-New-Grass-Revival-Live-And-Pickling-Fast/release/9390038 discogs.com, ''Live and Pickling Fast'']</ref> ''Live And Pickling Fast'' DVD was released with audio bonus tracks.<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Leon-Russell-And-The-New-Grass-Revival-Live-And-Pickling-Fast/release/11073312 discogs.com, DVD Live And Pickling Fast]</ref>\n\nIn 2006 Leon did a 12 city concert tour of the US. On April 23, 2006 Leon received the ''Living Legend award'' at [[Bare Bones International Film Festival]].<ref>[http://www.leonrussellrecords.com/news/042906.html Leon Russell Records Newsletter, April 29, 2006]</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, he was inducted into the [[Oklahoma Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>[https://rocklegendscruise.com/artists/leon-russell/ Rock Legends Cruise, Leon Russell]</ref>\n\nAt age 65, Russell made the new Okie rock album ''[[Angel in Disguise (Leon Russell album)|Angel in Disguise]]'', which was released by Leon Russell Records in 2006.<ref name=\"Thom Jurek\">{{cite web|author=Thom Jurek |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/angel-in-disguise-mw0000779301 |title=Angel in Disguise \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=August 7, 2007 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Bad Country (Leon Russell album)|Bad Country]]'' released on Leon Russell Records in 2007, with 12 original songs by Russell.<ref name=\"Stephen Thomas Erlewine\">{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/bad-country-mw0000585624 |title=Bad Country \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=[[AllMusic]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell played at [[Diversafest]], Tulsa's Music Conference and Festival in 2007. From 2002 to 2010, Dfest was an annual live event that showcased independent and emerging artists and hosted educational music industry panels and a tradeshow.  Over its last four years, Dfest was held in the historic Blue Dome District of [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]].\n\n''[[Almost Piano]]'' was released in 2007 by Leon Russell Records. It is a [[synthesizer]] piano collection of ten instrumentals from Russell.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/almost-piano-mw0000580354 |title=Almost Piano \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=[[AllMusic]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[In Your Dreams (Leon Russell album)|In Your Dreams]]'' was released on CD by Leon Russell Records in 2008.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/in-your-dreams-mw0000581964 |title=In Your Dreams \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |website=AllMusic |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Leon release ''[[A Mighty Flood]]'' a gospel album with original song by Leon. [[Billboard magazine]] on October 2, 2010, called a ''A Mighty Flood'' \"a recent treat\" and a \"buoyant 2008 gospel album\".<ref>Billboard Oct 2, 2010, Page 28, column 1, by Wayan Robin, \"A Mighty Flood is a recent treat\"</ref>\n\n===2010s===\nOn January 31, 2010 Leon join the [[Zac Brown Band]] to play the ''[[Chicken Fried]]'' on the Grammy Awards. Zac Brown Band won the [[Best New Artist]] award.<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/1630903/leon-russell-shines-with-zac-brown-band-at-the-grammys/ MTV, Leon Russell Shines With Zac Brown Band At The Grammys, Legendary keyboardist joins Best New Artist winners on their hit song 'Chicken Fried', 01/31/2010]</ref>\n\nIn 2010  Leon Russell's daughter, Sugaree Noel Bridges, released her first album ''The American Dream'' on Leon Russell Records.<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Sugaree-The-American-Dream/release/2941269 ''The American Dream'']</ref><ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-american-dream-mw0001792576 allmusic, Sugaree, ''The American Dream'']</ref>\n\nAfter years of reduced prominence, Russell's career was rejuvenated when Elton John sought him for a new project.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thespec.com/whatson/article/778650--leon-russell-enjoys-kickstart-from-elton-john | title=Leon Russell enjoys kickstart from Elton John | website=Thespec.com | date=August 11, 2012 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> In November 2009, Russell worked with John and [[Bernie Taupin]] on ''[[The Union (Elton John and Leon Russell album)|The Union]]'', a double album record credited equally to Russell and John. Recorded in February 2010 and produced by [[T-Bone Burnett]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.berniejtaupin.com/articles.bt?n_id=459564 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160317230819/http://www.berniejtaupin.com/articles.bt?n_id=459564 | url-status=dead | archive-date=March 17, 2016 | title=Bernie Taupin :: Articles | website=Berniejtaupin.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> the CD was released on October 19, 2010. ''The Union'' was Russell's sixth gold album.<ref>{{cite web | author=Tim Cashmere | url=http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=11444_Elton_John_and_Leon_Russell_Album_Cover_Revealed | title=Elton John and Leon Russell Album Cover Revealed \u2013 Undercover.fm News | website=Undercover.com.au | date=July 25, 2010 | accessdate=April 24, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727114627/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=11444_Elton_John_and_Leon_Russell_Album_Cover_Revealed |archivedate=July 27, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The recordings were interrupted in January 2010 when Russell was hospitalized and underwent surgery for a brain fluid leak, as well as treatment for heart failure and pneumonia.<ref name=NYT-2010>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/19/arts/music/19leon.html?_r=0 | title=A Superstar Puts One of His Early Influences Back in the Spotlight | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>  On April 2, 2011, Russell and John performed together as the musical guests on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' placed the album in third place on its list of the 30 Best Albums of 2010.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/30-best-albums-of-2010-20101213 |title=30 Best Albums of 2010 | magazine=Rolling Stone | accessdate=April 1, 2014}}</ref> A couple of months later, Russell announced plans for a solo LP, although no specifics were given, and in October 2010 Russell and John embarked on [[The Union Tour]]. John and Russell also appeared on the [[Late Show with David Letterman]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/leon-russell-elton-john-on-letterman-show/ | title=Leon Russell, Elton John On Letterman Show | publisher=CBS News | date=February 10, 2011 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRussell and John were nominated for their track \u201cIf It Wasn't for Bad\", from their ''The Union'' album, for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] at the [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards|2010 Grammy Awards]],<ref name=\"Grammy history\"/> which were presented on February 13, 2011.\n\nIn 2011, the documentary film ''[[The Union (2011 film)|The Union]]'' by [[Cameron Crowe]] was released. It explored the creative process of John and Russell in the making of the 2010 album ''The Union''.<ref>{{cite news | author=Mark Egan | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/06/21/us-leonrussell-idUSTRE75K2RL20110621 | title=No regrets for resurgent musician Leon Russell | work=[[Reuters]] | date=June 21, 2011 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I7K9EEa7CRs | title=Elton John and Leon Russell \u2013 The Union Documentary | date=November 19, 2014 | publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Russell played in [[Willie Nelson's Fourth of July Picnic]] in [[Fort Worth, Texas]] in 2013. He had first played at the picnic in 1976.<ref name=\"Chicago\">[http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-leon-russell-dead-20161113-story.html \"Rocker Leon Russell dead at 74\"], ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', November 13, 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.mauinews.com/life/maui-beat/2013/09/how-leon-russell-got-his-groove-back/ How Leon Russell got his groove back, Maui Beat, Sep 19, 2013]</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Leon and [[Vince Gill]] sang the song ''A Way to Survive'' on the ''[[Living for a Song]]: A Tribute to Hank Cochran'' studio album by [[Jamey Johnson]]. Along with strong critical acclaim, the album was nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Country Album]].<ref name=\"songwriter\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/11/jamey-johnson-living-for-a-song-a-tribute-to-hank-cochran/|title=Jamey Johnson: Living For A Song: A Tribute To Hank Cochran |magazine=American Songwriter|date=7 November 2012|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2013 Leon performed on the [[CMT Crossroads]] broadcast with Willie Nelson, [[Sheryl Crow]], [[Jamey Johnson]], [[Norah Jones]], [[Ashley Monroe]] and Neil Young.<ref>[CMT Willie Nelson\u2019s CMT Crossroads Debuts Sunday 6/21/2013]</ref>\n\n[[File:20160228-Leon Russell-JTG.jpg|thumbnail|Leon Russell taking time out to tell a story in  2016]]\n\nIn 2014, the album ''[[Life Journey]]'' was released on Universal Records. Working with [[Tommy LiPuma]], this album included two new songs by Russell: \"Big Lips\" and \"Down in Dixieland\".<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web | author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/life-journey-mw0002623344 | title=Life Journey \u2013 Leon Russell &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits | website=[[AllMusic]] | date=April 1, 2014 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2015, a restored version of a previously unreleased 1974 documentary about Russell, ''[[A Poem Is A Naked Person]]'' by filmmaker [[Les Blank]], was screened at the [[South by Southwest]] Film Festival.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2015/events/event_FS17794  | title=SxSW Film Schedule: A Poem is a Naked Person | website=Schedule.sxsw.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref> The film features concert footage of Russell in New Orleans and Anaheim and of the recording sessions for the album ''Hank Wilson's Back''.\n\nIn 2015, he played at Virginia's [[Lockn' Festival]] and the [[Wildflower! Arts and Music Festival]] in [[Richardson, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Kara Kunkel | title=Wildflower! Arts & Music Festival | work=Dallas News | date=March 4, 2005 }}</ref> On September 11, 2015, Russell joined [[Rita Coolidge]], [[Claudia Lennear]], [[Chris Stainton]], and other members of the 1970 ''Mad Dogs and Englishmen Tour'' for a tribute concert to Joe Cocker organized by the [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]].<ref>{{cite magazine | author=David Browne | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/inside-tedeschi-trucks-bands-all-star-joe-cocker-tribute-concert-20150714?page=2 | title=Page 2 of Inside Tedeschi Trucks Band's All-Star Joe Cocker Tribute Concert | magazine=Rolling Stone | date=July 14, 2015 | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/126495/Full-Show-Friday-Mad-Dogs-and-Englishmen-Tribute-At-Lockn | title=Full Show Friday &#124; Mad Dogs & Englishmen Tribute At Lockn | website=Jambase.com | accessdate=December 14, 2015}}</ref>  Original tour photographer [[Linda Wolf]] documented the reunion and performance.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://introvid.me/mad-dogs-and-englishmen | title=Player | website=Introvid.me | accessdate=December 14, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311063128/http://introvid.me/mad-dogs-and-englishmen | archive-date=March 11, 2016 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2015 Leon, [[Bonnie Raitt]] and [[Ivan Neville]] gave a performance at The Canyon Club in [[Agoura Hills, California]], Ca to raise cash for [[Marty Grebb]] who was battling cancer. Grebb had played on some of their albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://californiarocker.com/2015/05/30/bonnie-raitt-and-musician-friends-celebrate-marty-grebb-at-canyon-club-fundraiser/|title=Bonnie Raitt, Friends Rock to Raise Funds for Marty Grebb|date=May 30, 2015|website=Californiarocker.com}}</ref>\n\nRussell had a nationwide concert tour to enthusiastic crowds in 2016 and was planning to tour into 2017.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\nThe album ''[[On a Distant Shore]]'' recorded in 2016, was posthumously released in September 2017. The album has 12 songs written by Leon. Leon's daughters Coco Bridges and Sugaree Noel Bridges performs backing vocals on the album.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/review-leon-russells-on-a-distant-shore-is-a-powerful-goodbye-w504766 | title=Review: Leon Russell, \"On A Distant Shore\" Is a Powerful Posthumous Goodbye | author=David Browne | magazine=Rolling Stone | date=September 21, 2017 | accessdate=April 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/on-a-distant-shore-mw0003085757 allmusic.com,  ''On A Distant Shore'']</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Leon Russell among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\n{{quote box|align=right|width=25em|bgcolor=MistyRose|quote=I first saw Leon Russell in 1971 or 1972. Then, as now, Leon made everything happen when he took the stage. For heaven's sake, his rock and roll credits could fill up a big inscribed monolith, if they still made such things.|source=[[Elvis Costello]]<ref name=\"NYT-2010\"/>}}\n\nRussell died in his sleep at his suburban [[Nashville]] home in Mt. Juliet, Tennessee, on November 13, 2016, at the age of 74, his wife said in a statement on his website. In 2010, he had undergone surgery, and in July 2016 he suffered a heart attack. He was recovering from heart surgery.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-leonrussell-idUSKBN1380JM | title=Leon Russell, musician known for dynamic performances, dies at 74 | work=[[Reuters]] | date=November 13, 2016 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Russell's funeral was on November 18 at Victory Baptist Church in Mt. Juliet, Tennessee, and a public memorial was held at The [[Oral Roberts University]] [[Mabee Center]] on November 20 in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HuIMnqQS-mU|title=Leon Russell Memorial Service|first=|last=Victory Baptist Church, Mt Juliet TN|date=November 20, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>  He is interred at the Memorial Park Cemetery in Tulsa, Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leon Russell |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/172674705/leon-russell |website=Findagrave.com |accessdate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nElton John, who had once been Russell's opening act, acknowledged him as his \"biggest influence as a piano player, a singer and a songwriter.\"<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2016/11/13/elton-john-leon-russell/93766474/ | title=Elton John remembers 'mentor, inspiration' Leon Russell | author=Carly Mallenbaum | newspaper=[[USA Today]] | date=November 13, 2016 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-leonrussell-idUSKBN1380JM | title=Leon Russell, musician known for dynamic performances, dies at 74 | author=Bill Trott | work=[[Reuters]] | date=November 13, 2016 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> On hearing of Russell's death, he said: \"My darling Leon Russell passed away last night. He was a mentor, inspiration and so kind to me. I loved him and always will.\"<ref name=\"USA\"/> John once recalled:\n{{quote|When Mr. Russell's \"Greatest Hits\" album came on one day during the trip, I started to cry, it moved me so much.  His music takes me back to the most wonderful time in my life, and it makes me so angry that he's been forgotten.<ref name=\"NYT-2010\"/>}}\n\n[[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] vocalist [[Black Francis]] credits Russell with influencing his vocal style: \"I realise there's a certain kind of vocalising I do that takes its cue from Leon Russell. He sang in a [[Southern United States|Southern]] accent but it was very blown-out and exaggerated, very free and loose.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jun/29/black-francis-soundtrack-of-my-life-pixies | title=Black Francis: soundtrack of my life | author=Killian Fox | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=June 28, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOne of Russell's titles and signature nicknames is: ''Master of Space and Time''. <ref>[https://www.newsweek.com/master-space-and-time-leon-russell-dies-74-520552 Newsweek, 'Master of Space and Time' Leon Russell Dies at 74, By Reuters, Nov 13, 2016]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRussell had six children.<ref name=\"LATIMES1999\">{{cite news | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/feb/17/entertainment/ca-8746/2 | title=A Familiar Face in the Crowd: Leon Russell Has Changed the Music Over the Years but Has Kept the Look | author=Mike Boehm | newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] | date=February 17, 1999 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-ms-leon-russell-obit-20161113-story.html | title=Leon Russell dies at 74; hit songwriter, Wrecking Crew member, musical bridge builder | author=Todd Martens | newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] | date=November 13, 2016 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> His oldest daughter Blue was with Carla McHenry. She was born February 20, 1972 and was named Blueagle after Oklahoman and Native American Artist Acee Blue Eagle. Leon married Mary McCreary on June 20, 1975. Mary was a musical partner. They had two children, daughter Tina Rose and son '''Teddy Jack'''. Leon and Mary divorced on October 3, 1980.  He married '''Janet Lee Constantine''' on February 6, 1983. They had three daughters together, Sugaree Noel (born October 9, 1982), Honey (born January 19, 1986), and Coco (born April 29, 1990).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/nov/14/leon-russell-obituary|title=Leon Russell obituary|first=Dave|last=Laing|date=November 14, 2016|website=Theguardian.com}}</ref> In 2013 on [[Willie Nelson]]'s ''[[To All the Girls...]]'' album, Willie sang the song \"[[After the Fire Is Gone]]\" with Tina Rose.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/to-all-the-girls-mw0002573622 Allmusic, To All the Girls...]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio and live albums===\n<ref name=\"Softshoe\"/><ref name=\"auto9\"/>\n<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:125px;\"|[[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br /><small>([[List of music recording sales certifications|sales thresholds]])</small>\n|-\n! style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:75%;\"| [[Billboard 200|U.S.]]\n! style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:75%;\"| [[Top Country Albums|U.S. Country]]\n! style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:75%;\"| Canada\n! style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:75%;\"| Canada Country\n! style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:75%;\"| [[New Zealand Albums Chart|New Zealand]]\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[Look Inside the Asylum Choir]]'' <small>(with [[Marc Benno]])</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 201\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text